<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Krascheninnikovia</i> <i>lanata</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Artemisia</i> <i>nova</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>confertifolia</i>, <i>Chrysothamnus</i> <i>viscidiflorus</i>, <i>Coleogyne</i> <i>ramosissima</i> and <i>Picrothamnus</i> <i>desertorum</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 1.5 m; canopy is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is open or grassy. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Krascheninnikovia lanata</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy; no other species equaling or exceeding its cover (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Alkaline flats around playas and along drainages, plains, and old lakebeds above current drainages. Soils are thin to moderately deep rocky to silty clay loams that are calcareous, moderately alkaline, and sometimes saline.  </div>
</div>

        
