<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Krascheninnikovia lanata </i>is a short, long-lived shrub that is sensitive to fire and moderate to heavy grazing. Regeneration is from seed but is rare. The species is wide ranging from the northern Great Plains to southern Canada, south to New Mexico, and west to California (Santa Barbara and San Luis Obispo Cos.). Its main distribution is in the Great Basin (Carey 1995a, 1995b, 1995c). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Krascheninnikovia lanata </i>does not usually dominate stands over most of its California range, but it is in a component of other alliances, most commonly the <i>Artemisia tridentata, Atriplex confertifolia, Grayia spinosa, </i>and <i>Yucca brevifolia </i>alliances. Dominance is found in transmontane stands, which are small (< 3 ha), and typically in seasonally flooded or saturated shallow basins and flats. These stands of appear widely distributed as part of the <i>Artemisia </i>steppe in northeastern California, either occurring in monospecific stands or mixed with <i>Picrothamnus desertorum </i>(Young et al. 2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
