    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ai, Ak). Small stands occur in the Carrizo National Monument on fine grained sedimentary rock and in the Temblor Range on gypsum-rich soils.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Az). Stands exist in the vicinity of Maricopa at the southern end of the Great Valley.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ad, Af-h, Aj, Al, An). A few stands marginally dominated by <i>Krascheninnikovia lanata</i> are similar ecologically to those of the <i>Atriplex confertifolia, Grayia spinosa,</i> or <i>Salazaria mexicana</i> alliances (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dh-j). A stand exists in upper Chalfant Valley, and they are likely in Adobe Valley and similar areas.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba, Bc). Stands occur as islands in <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> ssp. <i>tridentata</i> scrub on the eastside of Surprise Valley, and probably in other closed basins and flats including the Fish Springs sub-basin of Honey Lake Valley (Young et al. 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-c). Small stands occur in Cowhorn and Little Cowhorn valleys in the Inyo Mountains, as upland stands along the eastern slopes (Young et al. 2007), and in the Cottonwood Mountains east of The Racetrack in Death Valley National Park.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Since fire is detrimental, we recommend fuel breaks to maintain stands. In burned sites, seeding is recommended before <i>Bromus tectorum </i>or other non-native annual grasses establish after fire. Abusive grazing practices have reduced and eliminated stands, but light grazing is not detrimental (Carey 1995a, b, c). Because this alliance is naturally rare in California and is sensitive to fire and moderate to heavy grazing, we should inventory and manage existing stands to maintain them. </div>
</div>

    

    

